    {
      "id": "b3xW2r9eX9rxc4vFLcnhw",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4047.7378257080163,
      "y": 283.2791964425792,
      "width": 1347.6837158203125,
      "height": 493.6600771231668,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ebfbee",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ac",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1178485728,
      "version": 352,
      "versionNonce": 869944261,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "RED ZONES:\n\nThe term red zone typically refers to a region of the stack defined by some calling conventions \n(notably, the System V AMD64 ABI used on most Unix-like systems) \nwhere a function (usually a leaf function that doesn’t call others) \ncan store temporary data without needing to adjust the stack pointer.\n\nThe red zone is a fixed area of memory, usually 128 bytes, \nlocated just below the current stack pointer. \n\nIt is guaranteed not to be clobbered by asynchronous events \n(like interrupts or signal handlers) during the execution of a function.\n\nIt allows functions to use this area for temporary data storage\n without having to modify the stack pointer. \nThis can improve performance by eliminating the overhead of stack adjustments for small, short-lived data.\n\nParticularly useful for leaf functions as they won't have to worry about changing data on the stack of other functions\nsince they don't call any!",
      "fontSize": 20.78568745781755,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "RED ZONES:\n\nThe term red zone typically refers to a region of the stack defined by some calling conventions \n(notably, the System V AMD64 ABI used on most Unix-like systems) \nwhere a function (usually a leaf function that doesn’t call others) \ncan store temporary data without needing to adjust the stack pointer.\n\nThe red zone is a fixed area of memory, usually 128 bytes, \nlocated just below the current stack pointer. \n\nIt is guaranteed not to be clobbered by asynchronous events \n(like interrupts or signal handlers) during the execution of a function.\n\nIt allows functions to use this area for temporary data storage\n without having to modify the stack pointer. \nThis can improve performance by eliminating the overhead of stack adjustments for small, short-lived data.\n\nParticularly useful for leaf functions as they won't have to worry about changing data on the stack of other functions\nsince they don't call any!",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "ts7nwY66pJwAEdVokBby1",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4034.8740311221372,
      "y": 953.3145654335281,
      "width": 1130.956318850319,
      "height": 262.281476713525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ebfbee",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ag",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 460527136,
      "version": 243,
      "versionNonce": 1184169739,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "SIMD [Simple Instruction Multiple Data]:\n\nIt's a technique used in modern CPUs (via instruction sets like MMX, SSE, AVX, etc.) \nto allow one instruction to perform the same operation on multiple pieces of data simultaneously. \n\nProblem --> In a kernel, context switches (system calls or interrupts) happen very frequently. \nWhen an interrupt occurs, the kernel must save the current state of all registers—including \nthese large SIMD registers—so that it can restore them later when the interrupted process resumes.\n\nDue to this problem .. may OSes may opt to disable this thing.. ",
      "fontSize": 20.982518137081986,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "SIMD [Simple Instruction Multiple Data]:\n\nIt's a technique used in modern CPUs (via instruction sets like MMX, SSE, AVX, etc.) \nto allow one instruction to perform the same operation on multiple pieces of data simultaneously. \n\nProblem --> In a kernel, context switches (system calls or interrupts) happen very frequently. \nWhen an interrupt occurs, the kernel must save the current state of all registers—including \nthese large SIMD registers—so that it can restore them later when the interrupted process resumes.\n\nDue to this problem .. may OSes may opt to disable this thing.. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "xdVVxyGUxAkdMfmcXelgw",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4059.946155012256,
      "y": 1306.8837609572256,
      "width": 1327.2889453252042,
      "height": 296.7117125438594,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ah",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 647633888,
      "version": 509,
      "versionNonce": 1485212453,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "VGA [Video Graphics Array]:\n\nThe VGA text buffer is a specific area of memory that your computer’s video \nhardware uses to display text on the screen. When you write to this area of memory, you change what appears on the screen.\n\nThe buffer is located at the fixed memory address 0xb8000. \nCan be addressed like normal memory and you can write into it.\nThe screen is usually set up as 25 rows by 80 columns.\nEach cell on the screen (each character position) is made up of 2 bytes:  -- check out the wikipedia page\n- 1 byte for the ASCII character (e.g., 'H', 'e', 'l', etc.)\n- 1 byte for the color (foreground and background -- the last bit is for blinking)\n",
      "fontSize": 19.780780836257293,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "VGA [Video Graphics Array]:\n\nThe VGA text buffer is a specific area of memory that your computer’s video \nhardware uses to display text on the screen. When you write to this area of memory, you change what appears on the screen.\n\nThe buffer is located at the fixed memory address 0xb8000. \nCan be addressed like normal memory and you can write into it.\nThe screen is usually set up as 25 rows by 80 columns.\nEach cell on the screen (each character position) is made up of 2 bytes:  -- check out the wikipedia page\n- 1 byte for the ASCII character (e.g., 'H', 'e', 'l', etc.)\n- 1 byte for the color (foreground and background -- the last bit is for blinking)\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "wu6yj03o4IuKt8i4UkrIO",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4063.8920594177175,
      "y": 1653.6339398673877,
      "width": 685.508544921875,
      "height": 237.79619530079748,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "cross-hatch",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dotted",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 80,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ak",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1538472928,
      "version": 803,
      "versionNonce": 1096213931,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "ELF [Executable and Linkable Format]:\n\ncommon standard format for executables, object code, \nshared libs and core dumps.\n\nfirst specified in an ABI for the SVR4 [System V Release 4]\n\nIt supports different endiannesses and address sizes -- \nso basically cross platform..",
      "fontSize": 21.13743958229311,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "ELF [Executable and Linkable Format]:\n\ncommon standard format for executables, object code, \nshared libs and core dumps.\n\nfirst specified in an ABI for the SVR4 [System V Release 4]\n\nIt supports different endiannesses and address sizes -- \nso basically cross platform..",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
