    {
      "id": "VZZDsEgYMi4lBcjITGkWF",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1402.620823978992,
      "y": 2606.8747377802547,
      "width": 1250.526123046875,
      "height": 417.49556268791343,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b06",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1578004972,
      "version": 271,
      "versionNonce": 749536267,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "UART [Universal Asynchronous Receiver-Transmitter]: \n\n- A universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter is a peripheral device for asynchronous serial communication \nin which the data format and transmission speeds are configurable. \n- It sends data bits one by one, from the least significant to the most significant, \nframed by start and stop bits so that precise timing is handled by the communication channel. \n- The electric signaling levels are handled by a driver circuit external to the UART. \n- Common signal levels are RS-232, RS-485, and raw TTL for short debugging links.\n\n\n- A UART is usually an individual (or part of an) integrated circuit (IC) used for \nserial communications over a computer or peripheral device serial port. \n- One or more UART peripherals are commonly integrated in microcontroller chips. \n\n\n- Data Link Layer in the OSI Model",
      "fontSize": 20.874778134395672,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "UART [Universal Asynchronous Receiver-Transmitter]: \n\n- A universal asynchronous receiver-transmitter is a peripheral device for asynchronous serial communication \nin which the data format and transmission speeds are configurable. \n- It sends data bits one by one, from the least significant to the most significant, \nframed by start and stop bits so that precise timing is handled by the communication channel. \n- The electric signaling levels are handled by a driver circuit external to the UART. \n- Common signal levels are RS-232, RS-485, and raw TTL for short debugging links.\n\n\n- A UART is usually an individual (or part of an) integrated circuit (IC) used for \nserial communications over a computer or peripheral device serial port. \n- One or more UART peripherals are commonly integrated in microcontroller chips. \n\n\n- Data Link Layer in the OSI Model",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
