    {
      "id": "jVvsp2XUe5hs62S0-0dVr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 384.9734628121272,
      "y": 2564.0558350985534,
      "width": 1451.9981689453125,
      "height": 425,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dotted",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0T",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1875066947,
      "version": 562,
      "versionNonce": 649070859,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Interrupt Descriptor Table:\n\nAn Interrupt Descriptor Table (IDT) is a data structure used by x86 and x86_64 processors that tells the CPU which function \n(or handler) to call when an interrupt or exception occurs. \n\nThink of it as a lookup table that maps various interrupt vectors (numeric identifiers) to their corresponding handler routines. \nThis allows the system to respond quickly and appropriately when an external event (like hardware signals) or internal error occurs.\n\nGlobal Descriptor Table:\n\nThey are used by the CPU to define characteristics of different memory areas to help during execution. \nIt helps with memory segmentation. Some characteristics could be like base address, size, memory type, access privileges, etc.\n\n\nFile Descriptors:\n\nUsed in UNIX like systems, to denote open files, sockets, etc. helpful for performing IO operations.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Interrupt Descriptor Table:\n\nAn Interrupt Descriptor Table (IDT) is a data structure used by x86 and x86_64 processors that tells the CPU which function \n(or handler) to call when an interrupt or exception occurs. \n\nThink of it as a lookup table that maps various interrupt vectors (numeric identifiers) to their corresponding handler routines. \nThis allows the system to respond quickly and appropriately when an external event (like hardware signals) or internal error occurs.\n\nGlobal Descriptor Table:\n\nThey are used by the CPU to define characteristics of different memory areas to help during execution. \nIt helps with memory segmentation. Some characteristics could be like base address, size, memory type, access privileges, etc.\n\n\nFile Descriptors:\n\nUsed in UNIX like systems, to denote open files, sockets, etc. helpful for performing IO operations.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "JNjjjnFRC_1UkCw0V5Sfn",
