      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "BREAKPOINT INSTRUCTIONS:\n\nA breakpoint exception is an event triggered by the CPU when it encounters a special instruction \n(often called a breakpoint instruction) that’s been inserted into a program to signal a debugger.\n\nBreakpoint Instruction:\n- In many CPU architectures (like x86), there is an instruction (for example, INT 3 on x86) \nthat intentionally causes an exception. This is used by debuggers to pause program execution at a specific point.\n\nException Handling:\n- When the CPU executes the breakpoint instruction, it generates a breakpoint exception. \nThis exception transfers control to a debugger or a dedicated exception handler that can inspect the program’s state, such as registers and memory.\n\nUse in Debugging:\n- Breakpoints allow a developer to stop execution at a particular line of code to analyze the state of the application, \nstep through code, and diagnose issues.\n\n-----------------How It Works -----------------\n\nInserting a Breakpoint:\n- A debugger typically writes a breakpoint instruction into the code at the location where you want execution to pause.\n\nTriggering the Exception:\n- When the CPU reaches that instruction, it raises a breakpoint exception.\n\nDebugger Intervention:\n- The debugger catches this exception, halts the program, and lets you inspect the program state or control the execution (step over, step into, etc.).",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "BREAKPOINT INSTRUCTIONS:\n\nA breakpoint exception is an event triggered by the CPU when it encounters a special instruction \n(often called a breakpoint instruction) that’s been inserted into a program to signal a debugger.\n\nBreakpoint Instruction:\n- In many CPU architectures (like x86), there is an instruction (for example, INT 3 on x86) \nthat intentionally causes an exception. This is used by debuggers to pause program execution at a specific point.\n\nException Handling:\n- When the CPU executes the breakpoint instruction, it generates a breakpoint exception. \nThis exception transfers control to a debugger or a dedicated exception handler that can inspect the program’s state, such as registers and memory.\n\nUse in Debugging:\n- Breakpoints allow a developer to stop execution at a particular line of code to analyze the state of the application, \nstep through code, and diagnose issues.\n\n-----------------How It Works -----------------\n\nInserting a Breakpoint:\n- A debugger typically writes a breakpoint instruction into the code at the location where you want execution to pause.\n\nTriggering the Exception:\n- When the CPU reaches that instruction, it raises a breakpoint exception.\n\nDebugger Intervention:\n- The debugger catches this exception, halts the program, and lets you inspect the program state or control the execution (step over, step into, etc.).",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "GkTvOK9YnR-kDZB7mmflS",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -4682.89593427328,
      "y": 956.6836543767979,
      "width": 538.9993286132812,
      "height": 275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dotted",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0X",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 544497635,
      "version": 496,
      "versionNonce": 1031843755,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "SSE [Streaming SIMD Extensions]:\n\n- This is just an extension of the previous\ninstruction sets made by Intel.\n- They are particularly efficient when they work \non multiple data all at once since SIMD..uk\n\n- There are others too like MMX ... that is\nalso one such instruction set .. check it out\n- SSE has been extended into more versions\nlike SSE2, SSE3, SSE4...",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "SSE [Streaming SIMD Extensions]:\n\n- This is just an extension of the previous\ninstruction sets made by Intel.\n- They are particularly efficient when they work \non multiple data all at once since SIMD..uk\n\n- There are others too like MMX ... that is\nalso one such instruction set .. check it out\n- SSE has been extended into more versions\nlike SSE2, SSE3, SSE4...",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
