    },
    {
      "id": "yqB2Woy8ouUgiCnglJlzd",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -6411.6005694527585,
      "y": 1453.0953302376367,
      "width": 1418.998291015625,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 80,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0l",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1283151389,
      "version": 74,
      "versionNonce": 1921436165,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "kfBKg1GDjvG11uT0sFoDD",
          "type": "arrow"
        },
        {
          "id": "gWZ1yuyRjI6NJkow0Q5AZ",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "GUARD PAGE:\n\n- A guard page is a special memory page at the bottom of a stack that makes it possible to detect stack overflows. \n- The page is not mapped to any physical frame, so accessing it causes a page fault instead of silently corrupting other memory. \n- The bootloader sets up a guard page for our kernel stack, so a stack overflow causes a page fault.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "GUARD PAGE:\n\n- A guard page is a special memory page at the bottom of a stack that makes it possible to detect stack overflows. \n- The page is not mapped to any physical frame, so accessing it causes a page fault instead of silently corrupting other memory. \n- The bootloader sets up a guard page for our kernel stack, so a stack overflow causes a page fault.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "1SD8h5abp-su5eseL7Nas",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -8164.0508215706805,
      "y": 838.2225810066635,
      "width": 1517.9981689453125,
      "height": 325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0m",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2135423474,
      "version": 327,
      "versionNonce": 1973847243,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "INTERRUPT STACK FRAME:\n\n- An interrupt stack frame is the collection of data that the CPU automatically saves on the stack when an interrupt or exception occurs. \n\n* This typically includes:\n\n- The return address (where to continue after the handler finishes).\n- The current CPU state (e.g., instruction pointer, code segment, flags).\n- Sometimes, additional error codes or register values depending on the type of interrupt.\n\n* Purpose:\n- The stack frame preserves the state of the interrupted task so that, after the interrupt handler finishes, \n    the CPU can restore this state and resume normal execution.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "INTERRUPT STACK FRAME:\n\n- An interrupt stack frame is the collection of data that the CPU automatically saves on the stack when an interrupt or exception occurs. \n\n* This typically includes:\n\n- The return address (where to continue after the handler finishes).\n- The current CPU state (e.g., instruction pointer, code segment, flags).\n- Sometimes, additional error codes or register values depending on the type of interrupt.\n\n* Purpose:\n- The stack frame preserves the state of the interrupted task so that, after the interrupt handler finishes, \n    the CPU can restore this state and resume normal execution.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "v_gp-xDq997grNzjM_1Dn",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -8171.815288872442,
      "y": 1260.0945538695748,
      "width": 1275.9984130859375,
      "height": 325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0n",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1306042158,
      "version": 83,
      "versionNonce": 25772389,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "INTERRUPT STACK TABLE:\n\n- The Interrupt Stack Table is a part of the Task State Segment (TSS). \n- It is an array of pointers (stack addresses) that specifies dedicated stacks for certain interrupts or exceptions.\n\n* Usage:\n\n- For critical exceptions (like a double fault), the CPU uses a dedicated stack defined in the IST. \n- This is crucial because the normal stack might be corrupted or overflown, so having a separate, \n    known-good stack ensures that the handler can run reliably.\n\n* Example: In the TSS, you might set the 0th IST entry to point to a statically \n            allocated stack that will be used exclusively for handling double faults.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "INTERRUPT STACK TABLE:\n\n- The Interrupt Stack Table is a part of the Task State Segment (TSS). \n- It is an array of pointers (stack addresses) that specifies dedicated stacks for certain interrupts or exceptions.\n\n* Usage:\n\n- For critical exceptions (like a double fault), the CPU uses a dedicated stack defined in the IST. \n- This is crucial because the normal stack might be corrupted or overflown, so having a separate, \n    known-good stack ensures that the handler can run reliably.\n\n* Example: In the TSS, you might set the 0th IST entry to point to a statically \n            allocated stack that will be used exclusively for handling double faults.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "7XYgSplAcoGjkOblmKY5x",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -9760.691829684876,
      "y": 892.5959589093882,
      "width": 1277.4553223240016,
      "height": 520.4048374062387,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#a5d8ff",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0o",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1376523566,
      "version": 292,
      "versionNonce": 665957227,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "0oDyuVzmjtCEi0szXGQX2",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "TASK STATE SEGMENT [TSS}:\n\n- The TSS is a data structure used by x86 processors that stores information about a task's state. \n- Originally, it was used for hardware task switching in older x86 operating systems. \n- In modern systems, while hardware task switching is rarely used, \n    the TSS is still used for:\n\n* Interrupt Stack Table: Providing dedicated stacks for certain interrupts (via IST entries).\n\n* Other State Information: It can also hold other control information \n                    (though in modern OS kernels, most context switching is managed in software).\n\n* Key Role:\n\n- The TSS helps the CPU switch to a safe stack when handling critical exceptions. \n- The operating system sets up a TSS and loads its address into a special CPU register (the TR register), \n    so the processor knows where to find the IST.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 21.911782627631116,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "TASK STATE SEGMENT [TSS}:\n\n- The TSS is a data structure used by x86 processors that stores information about a task's state. \n- Originally, it was used for hardware task switching in older x86 operating systems. \n- In modern systems, while hardware task switching is rarely used, \n    the TSS is still used for:\n\n* Interrupt Stack Table: Providing dedicated stacks for certain interrupts (via IST entries).\n\n* Other State Information: It can also hold other control information \n                    (though in modern OS kernels, most context switching is managed in software).\n\n* Key Role:\n\n- The TSS helps the CPU switch to a safe stack when handling critical exceptions. \n- The operating system sets up a TSS and loads its address into a special CPU register (the TR register), \n    so the processor knows where to find the IST.\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
