    {
      "id": "BX2W6ERIe8qUTv_1oyMlf",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -9880.905547737124,
      "y": 1551.7469964976053,
      "width": 1515.5892419947418,
      "height": 552.1757777286716,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#6741d9",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0t",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1886115058,
      "version": 297,
      "versionNonce": 1315312811,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "RBQfYGwSjBovvbVlCey5G",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "GLOBAL DESCRIPTOR TABLE [GDT]:\n\n- The Global Descriptor Table is a fundamental data structure in x86 architecture that defines memory segments. \n- Each entry in the GDT is called a descriptor, and these descriptors tell the CPU:\n\n> The base address of a memory segment.\n> The segment's limit (size).\n> Access rights and privilege levels.\n\n* Uses:\n\n- Segmentation: Although modern operating systems typically use paging instead of segmentation, \n    the GDT is still required. For example, a GDT entry is used to define the code and data segments for the kernel and user-space.\n\n- TSS Descriptor: One of the entries in the GDT is dedicated to the TSS. \n       This entry tells the CPU where the TSS is located and its size.\n\n* Importance:\n- The GDT sets up the basic memory model that the CPU uses to translate logical addresses to linear addresses.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 21.035267722997013,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "GLOBAL DESCRIPTOR TABLE [GDT]:\n\n- The Global Descriptor Table is a fundamental data structure in x86 architecture that defines memory segments. \n- Each entry in the GDT is called a descriptor, and these descriptors tell the CPU:\n\n> The base address of a memory segment.\n> The segment's limit (size).\n> Access rights and privilege levels.\n\n* Uses:\n\n- Segmentation: Although modern operating systems typically use paging instead of segmentation, \n    the GDT is still required. For example, a GDT entry is used to define the code and data segments for the kernel and user-space.\n\n- TSS Descriptor: One of the entries in the GDT is dedicated to the TSS. \n       This entry tells the CPU where the TSS is located and its size.\n\n* Importance:\n- The GDT sets up the basic memory model that the CPU uses to translate logical addresses to linear addresses.\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
