    {
      "id": "TOVLROn7f-THzlHEh-MAK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -11758.95923387746,
      "y": 1756.3750683076696,
      "width": 1748.2569113262716,
      "height": 686.0402136808735,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#f3f0ff",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b0w",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2028739122,
      "version": 373,
      "versionNonce": 336520933,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "Nqwn-MT4Mj0ignPAxn-mz",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1775334275199,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "HARDWARE CONTEXT SWITCHING:\n\n- Hardware context switching is the process by which a CPU switches from executing one task (or thread) to another. \n- This involves saving the state of the current task and restoring the state of the next task.\n\n* What’s Saved:\n\n- General-purpose registers.\n- Instruction pointer.\n- Flags register.\n- Possibly segment registers and other special registers.\n\n* How It Works:\n\n> Saving Context: When an interrupt occurs or the scheduler decides to switch tasks, \n                    the CPU (or the operating system’s interrupt handler) saves the current task’s CPU state.\n\n> Restoring Context: The scheduler then selects a new task to run, and its previously saved state is restored, \n                        so the CPU resumes executing that task as if it had never been interrupted.\n\n* Modern OS Behavior: \n\n- While older x86 systems supported automatic, hardware-assisted task switching via the TSS, \n    most modern operating systems perform context switching in software (using the TSS only for specific purposes like IST for interrupts).",
      "fontSize": 22.868007122695772,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "HARDWARE CONTEXT SWITCHING:\n\n- Hardware context switching is the process by which a CPU switches from executing one task (or thread) to another. \n- This involves saving the state of the current task and restoring the state of the next task.\n\n* What’s Saved:\n\n- General-purpose registers.\n- Instruction pointer.\n- Flags register.\n- Possibly segment registers and other special registers.\n\n* How It Works:\n\n> Saving Context: When an interrupt occurs or the scheduler decides to switch tasks, \n                    the CPU (or the operating system’s interrupt handler) saves the current task’s CPU state.\n\n> Restoring Context: The scheduler then selects a new task to run, and its previously saved state is restored, \n                        so the CPU resumes executing that task as if it had never been interrupted.\n\n* Modern OS Behavior: \n\n- While older x86 systems supported automatic, hardware-assisted task switching via the TSS, \n    most modern operating systems perform context switching in software (using the TSS only for specific purposes like IST for interrupts).",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
